T1  - SEARCH AND THE SOURCES OF LIFE-CYCLE INEQUALITY
AU  - Griffy, Benjamin S.
Y1  - 2021/11/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12522
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1321
EP  - 1362
VL  - 62
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12522
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract I study how initial wealth affects lifetime earnings inequality when labor markets are frictional. To do this, I construct a model life-cycle model with search frictions, incomplete markets, and endogenous human capital accumulation. In the model, incomplete markets prevent low-wealth workers from smoothing consumption, causing them to accept low pay jobs while unemployed. In anticipation, they build savings instead of human capital while employed. This amplifies the importance of initial wealth for life-cycle inequality. Using this model, I find that differences in initial wealth cause larger differences in lifetime earnings than either initial human capital or ability.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - WHY DO AMERICANS SPEND SO MUCH MORE ON HEALTH CARE THAN EUROPEANS?
AU  - He, Hui
AU  - Huang, Kevin X.D.
AU  - Ning, Lei
Y1  - 2021/11/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12527
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1363
EP  - 1399
VL  - 62
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12527
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Empirical evidence shows that both leisure and medical care are important in maintaining health and taxation may affect the allocation of these two inputs. We highlight this point using an analytical setting whose implications conform to micro- and macro-data. We then quantify these implications using a life-cycle overlapping generations model where taxation and relative health-care price are key determinants of the composition of the two inputs in the endogenous accumulation of health capital. We find that differences in taxation alone explain 44.7% of U.S.?EU differences in health expenditure?GDP ratio and more than 70% of their differences in time allocation.
ER  - 

